BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:ford-foundation-technology-fellow-digital-safety-security-2026@artifici
 alnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260707T130726Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260706
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260707
SUMMARY:Deadline: Technology Fellow: Digital Safety and Security
DESCRIPTION:The Ford Foundation seeks a two-year Technology Fellow for Digi
 tal Safety and Security to expand the foundation's ability to support gran
 tee digital safety and security. Civil society organizations face targeted
  information security threats yet many lack the resources and training to 
 maintain robust digital security. Reporting to the Director\, Office of th
 e Vice President for U.S. Programs\, the Fellow will identify field-buildi
 ng opportunities in the public-interest digital safety and security field\
 , work directly with program officers across US and global teams to integr
 ate digital security capacity into Ford's technical assistance programs\, 
 provide strategic support to high-risk grantees\, and assess strategic gap
 s in the ecosystem for safety and security providers. The Technology Fello
 ws Program is administered by Ford's Technology and Society Program and is
  designed to increase sociotechnical capacity within the Foundation. Requi
 rements include a minimum of 7 years' professional experience with media\,
  technology\, advocacy or policy organizations\; a baccalaureate degree or
  equivalent experience\; sophisticated knowledge of existing and emerging 
 technologies with a focus on surveillance technologies and organizational 
 digital safety and security\; and experience designing\, implementing or s
 upporting digital safety and security solutions in a complex global settin
 g. Hybrid role based in New York (three days per week in office) with appr
 oximately 10 to 20 percent domestic and international travel. Not eligible
  for visa sponsorship\; candidates must be authorized to work in the Unite
 d States. Submit both a resume and a cover letter to be considered.\n\nOrg
 anisation: Ford Foundation\nLocation: New York\, New York\, USA\nAward: US
 D 166\,000 to 170\,000 annual salary\, plus comprehensive benefits and ret
 irement contributions of up to 13%\nDuration: Two-year term-limited contra
 ct\n\nMore: https://fordfoundation.wd1.myworkdayjobs.com/en-US/FordFoundat
 ionCareerPage/details/Technology-Fellow--Digital-Safety-and-Security_R1295
URL:https://fordfoundation.wd1.myworkdayjobs.com/en-US/FordFoundationCareer
 Page/details/Technology-Fellow--Digital-Safety-and-Security_R1295
LOCATION:New York\, New York\, USA
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:tech-workers-coalition-circuit-breakers-2026@artificialnouveau.github.i
 o
DTSTAMP:20260707T130726Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260715
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260716
SUMMARY:Deadline: Circuit Breakers '26: Tech Worker Conference - Call for P
 roposals (New York City)
DESCRIPTION:Circuit Breakers '26 is a tech worker conference organised by v
 olunteers from across the tech labour movement\, bringing together workers
 \, organisers and activists in the tech industry to learn\, build communit
 y and strategise. Tech Workers Coalition defines tech workers broadly\, fr
 om software engineers and salespeople to warehouse workers and ride-share 
 drivers. The conference centres rank-and-file organising\, with workers sh
 aring stories\, running skills trainings and leading debates. The open cal
 l for proposals welcomes sessions on all aspects of labour organising in t
 ech\, with particular interest in three areas: Labor Organizing Against Im
 perialism\; Tech Workers Taking on Technology (layoffs\, surveillance\, wo
 rker control over AI and automation)\; and Bold Strategy (solidarity\, mem
 bership structures\, return-to-office actions\, cross-border organising). 
 Sessions can be proposed via a short form (about 10 minutes). New York Cit
 y\, 17-18 October 2026. This is not a grant and carries no funding\; it is
  a free call for conference talks. NOTE: the call-for-proposals deadline w
 as not yet published at time of listing\; confirm the submission deadline 
 and form link on the Circuit Breakers page.\n\nOrganisation: Tech Workers 
 Coalition\nLocation: New York City\, USA. In-person conference 17-18 Octob
 er 2026. Open to workers across the tech sector\, from software engineers 
 and salespeople to warehouse workers\, ride-share drivers and contractors.
 \nAward: No funding. This is a free call for talk/session proposals at a v
 olunteer-organised tech labour conference\, not a grant. No submission fee
 .\nDuration: Two-day conference\, 17-18 October 2026.\n\nMore: https://tec
 hworkerscoalition.org/circuit-breakers/
URL:https://techworkerscoalition.org/circuit-breakers/
LOCATION:New York City\, USA. In-person conference 17-18 October 2026. Open
  to workers across the tech sector\, from software engineers and salespeop
 le to warehouse workers\, ride-share drivers and contractors.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:project-liberty-co-lab-fund-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260707T130726Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260621
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260622
SUMMARY:Deadline: Project Liberty: Co-Lab Fund Member Collaboration Grants 
 (Round 1\, 2026)
DESCRIPTION:MEMBERS ONLY: this is a member-led collaboration fund\, not an 
 open public call. Projects must be led by a Project Liberty Coalition (All
 iance) member organization. The Co-Lab Fund\, launched by the coalition's 
 Steering Committee (SteerCo)\, supports projects that Coalition members un
 dertake together\, building on the trust and relationships that already ex
 ist within the community so that funding decisions can rest on the strengt
 h of the idea\, the people behind it\, and their track records rather than
  extensive diligence. In exchange for a streamlined process\, grants stay 
 modest and funded teams share their progress with the broader Coalition as
  projects develop\, creating accountability and letting the community lear
 n from what emerges. Two kinds of projects qualify: (1) work that advances
  the Coalition's active workstreams (listed in the application)\, and (2) 
 investment in the Coalition's connective infrastructure\, such as shared s
 ervices and resources that strengthen collective capacity. Eligibility: pr
 ojects must be led by a Coalition member organization\, produce value for 
 more than one Coalition organization\, begin substantive work within a few
  weeks of approval\, and fall within the active workstreams\; full eligibi
 lity details are in the Overview and FAQ document. How it works: monthly r
 ounds are planned until December 2026 or until the funds are disbursed\; t
 he application is designed to take an hour or less once the project's shap
 e is clear\, and decisions are expected within about three weeks of each d
 eadline. This is the first cycle and the Fund is being built as it goes\, 
 so the process is expected to improve each round. Round 1 closes Sunday\, 
 21 June 2026\; further rounds follow\, so there is no need to force an ide
 a into this cycle. Apply via the Fillout application form.\n\nOrganisation
 : Project Liberty (Alliance SteerCo)\; pooled fund supported by Future of 
 Life Institute\, Omidyar Network\, Ergo Impact\, and Project Liberty\nLoca
 tion: Members of the Project Liberty coalition (Alliance). Projects led by
  a Coalition member organization\; geography otherwise unrestricted.\nAwar
 d: Grants cap at USD 250\,000 per project\; most first-round awards fall b
 etween USD 25\,000 and USD 100\,000. Pooled fund supported by Future of Li
 fe Institute\, Omidyar Network\, Ergo Impact\, and Project Liberty. No app
 lication fee.\nDuration: Project length varies. Funding rounds run monthly
  until December 2026\, or until the funds are disbursed\; decisions are ex
 pected within roughly three weeks of each deadline.\n\nMore: https://forms
 .fillout.com/t/6AGEGhTkNJus
URL:https://forms.fillout.com/t/6AGEGhTkNJus
LOCATION:Members of the Project Liberty coalition (Alliance). Projects led 
 by a Coalition member organization\; geography otherwise unrestricted.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:techcongress-congressional-innovation-fellowship-2027@artificialnouveau
 .github.io
DTSTAMP:20260707T130726Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260626
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260627
SUMMARY:Deadline: TechCongress: Congressional Innovation Fellowship 2027 (S
 enior and Early-Career)
DESCRIPTION:TechCongress places technologists in the US Congress to build t
 echnology capacity among Members and Congressional staff\, where fewer tha
 n 3% of legislative staff have a technical background. For the January 202
 7 cohort it is recruiting up to twenty fellows (10 for Democratic offices\
 , 10 for Republican offices) across two tiers: the Senior Congressional In
 novation Fellowship (mid-career\, at least eight years of work or postgrad
 uate study) and the Congressional Innovation Fellowship (early-career\, tw
 o to six years of experience\, including a recently finished or projected-
 by-January-2027 graduate technical degree such as a Masters or PhD\; appli
 cants with seven years qualify for an intermediate tier). Fellows choose a
  placement with a Member of Congress or a Congressional Committee\, report
  to a senior staffer (such as a Chief of Staff or Staff Director)\, and do
  work similar to other Congressional staff: researching tech policy (cyber
  and election security\, data and biometric privacy\, AI policy\, autonomo
 us vehicles\, health IT\, encryption\, disinformation)\, educating Members
  and staff\, writing legislation\, preparing Committee hearings\, markups 
 and investigations\, and building coalitions. No prior government experien
 ce is required\; the fellowship is first and foremost an educational exper
 ience. This year TechCongress also seeks at least two fellows from non-tra
 ditional verticals: climate (grid modernization\, clean energy\, NEPA refo
 rm)\, government innovation (govtech and digital benefits delivery\, civil
  service reform)\, and science\, research and innovation (NSF\, NIH\, DoE\
 , FDA reform\, clinical trials). Technical degrees or experience in engine
 ering\, development\, journalism\, scientific\, legal or government roles 
 are encouraged. TechCongress is a nonpartisan nonprofit incubated at the O
 pen Technology Institute at New America\; since 2016 it has sent 140 fello
 ws to Congress. Equal opportunity employer. Application deadline: 26 June 
 2026\, 5:59am (applicant's local timezone). Contact: aleena@techcongress.i
 o. Apply via the official application form.\n\nOrganisation: TechCongress\
 nLocation: Washington\, DC\, United States. Full-time\, in-person\; remote
  participation is not possible. Nonpartisan: fellows serve in both Democra
 tic and Republican offices.\nAward: Senior (mid-career) Fellows: USD 100\,
 600/year stipend. Early-career Fellows: USD 78\,000 annual-equivalent stip
 end (USD 6\,500/month). Plus health insurance supplement up to USD 425/mon
 th\, up to USD 2\,000 relocation to DC\, up to USD 2\,000 first-month shor
 t-term housing reimbursement\, up to USD 2\,000 official travel\, and a US
 D 500 professional-attire allowance. No application fee.\nDuration: Senior
  Fellows serve January to December 2027 (optional one-month extension). Ea
 rly-career Fellows serve January to October 2027.\n\nMore: https://techcon
 gress.forms.fm/january-2027-fellowship/forms/10111
URL:https://techcongress.forms.fm/january-2027-fellowship/forms/10111
LOCATION:Washington\, DC\, United States. Full-time\, in-person\; remote pa
 rticipation is not possible. Nonpartisan: fellows serve in both Democratic
  and Republican offices.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:eic-accelerator-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260707T130726Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260708
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260709
SUMMARY:Deadline: EIC Accelerator 2026 (European Innovation Council)
DESCRIPTION:The EIC Accelerator funds high-risk\, high-impact deep-tech SME
 s and start-ups to develop and scale breakthrough innovations. It offers a
  grant of up to EUR 2.5 million (a non-dilutive lump sum) for innovation a
 ctivities\, and can combine this with an equity investment of EUR 1-10 mil
 lion through the EIC Fund (blended finance)\, or provide investment only. 
 The Step 1 short application can be submitted at any time\; full (Step 2) 
 applications are evaluated at fixed cut-offs. The next 2026 cut-offs are 8
  July\, 2 September and 4 November 2026 (all 17:00 Brussels time). Eligibl
 e applicants are for-profit SMEs and start-ups (fewer than 250 employees\,
  turnover up to EUR 50M or balance sheet up to EUR 43M) established in an 
 EU Member State or Horizon Europe Associated Country\; small mid-caps up t
 o 499 employees are eligible for investment-only support. Apply via the EU
  Funding and Tenders portal (topic HORIZON-EIC-2026-ACCELERATOR-01).\n\nOr
 ganisation: European Innovation Council (European Commission)\nLocation: E
 U Member States and Horizon Europe Associated Countries. Single-company ap
 plicants\; third-country applicants must relocate before the full-applicat
 ion stage.\nAward: Grant up to EUR 2.5 million (non-dilutive lump sum) for
  innovation activities\, plus optional equity investment of EUR 1-10 milli
 on via the EIC Fund. Options: grant-only\, blended finance\, or investment
 -only. No application fee.\nDuration: Project-based\; supports development
  and scale-up at TRL 5/6 to 8.\n\nMore: https://eic.ec.europa.eu/eic-fundi
 ng-opportunities/eic-accelerator_en
URL:https://eic.ec.europa.eu/eic-funding-opportunities/eic-accelerator_en
LOCATION:EU Member States and Horizon Europe Associated Countries. Single-c
 ompany applicants\; third-country applicants must relocate before the full
 -application stage.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:eurostars-call-11-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260707T130726Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260910
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260911
SUMMARY:Deadline: Eurostars Call 11 2026 (Eureka / Eurostars-3)
DESCRIPTION:Eurostars (part of the Eureka network\, the Eurostars-3 program
 me co-funded by Horizon Europe) supports collaborative international R&D p
 rojects led by innovative SMEs. Each country funds its own participants\, 
 so amounts vary\; for the Dutch share\, RVO funds up to EUR 500\,000 per p
 roject at a 50 percent reimbursement rate on eligible R&D costs. Projects 
 require an international consortium of at least two independent organisati
 ons from at least two Eurostars countries\, led by an innovative SME\, wit
 h the SME budget at least 50 percent of the total and no single participan
 t exceeding 70 percent. Projects must run no longer than 36 months and be 
 civil (non-defence) in purpose. Call 11 opens 9 July 2026 and closes 10 Se
 ptember 2026\, 14:00 CEST. No application fee. Submit via the Eureka proje
 ct platform (myeurekaproject.org)\; Dutch national information at RVO.\n\n
 Organisation: Eureka / Eurostars-3 (Dutch participation via RVO)\nLocation
 : International consortia from at least two Eurostars countries\, led by a
 n innovative SME. Dutch funding administered by RVO.\nAward: Co-funds coll
 aborative international R&D\; national funding varies by country. For the 
 Dutch project share: up to EUR 500\,000 per project at 50 percent reimburs
 ement of eligible R&D costs. No application fee.\nDuration: Projects up to
  36 months.\n\nMore: https://www.eurekanetwork.org/programmes-and-calls/eu
 rostars/eurostars-call-for-projects-september-2026/
URL:https://www.eurekanetwork.org/programmes-and-calls/eurostars/eurostars-
 call-for-projects-september-2026/
LOCATION:International consortia from at least two Eurostars countries\, le
 d by an innovative SME. Dutch funding administered by RVO.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:mit-rd-samenwerking-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260707T130726Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260915
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260916
SUMMARY:Deadline: MIT R&D Collaboration Projects 2026 (MKB Innovatiestimule
 ring Topsectoren)
DESCRIPTION:The MIT R&D Collaboration Projects scheme (MIT R&D-samenwerking
 sprojecten\, part of MKB Innovatiestimulering Topsectoren) funds joint R&D
  projects by Dutch SMEs within the national Top Sectors and Mission-driven
  Innovation policy. The grant covers 35 percent of eligible costs: small p
 rojects of EUR 50\,000-200\,000 and large projects of EUR 200\,000-350\,00
 0 (with per-participant ranges of EUR 25\,000-100\,000 for small and EUR 2
 5\,000-175\,000 for large). Eligible applicants are consortia of at least 
 two collaborating SMEs\, with no single participant carrying more than 70 
 percent of costs. The national RVO round runs 9 June to 15 September 2026 
 (closes 17:00) and is a ranked tender\, not first-come-first-served\; some
  provinces run separate regional MIT windows. No application fee. Apply vi
 a RVO.\n\nOrganisation: Rijksdienst voor Ondernemend Nederland (RVO)\nLoca
 tion: Netherlands. SME consortia (minimum two collaborating SMEs).\nAward:
  Grant covering 35 percent of eligible costs. Small projects EUR 50\,000-2
 00\,000\; large projects EUR 200\,000-350\,000 per project (EUR 25\,000-10
 0\,000 or EUR 25\,000-175\,000 per participant). No application fee.\nDura
 tion: Project-based\; ranked tender (not first-come).\n\nMore: https://www
 .rvo.nl/subsidies-financiering/mit/rd-samenwerkingsprojecten
URL:https://www.rvo.nl/subsidies-financiering/mit/rd-samenwerkingsprojecten
LOCATION:Netherlands. SME consortia (minimum two collaborating SMEs).
END:VEVENT
